<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  This is the prior-art grounding for the two <strong>vision</strong> items on the
  design-reference screenshot corpus: the <em>capture-time QC gate</em>
  (<a href="/backlog/475-design-ref-vision-gated-capture-qc-candidate-surface-quality/">backlog #475</a>)
  and the <em>codification pass</em>
  (<a href="/backlog/396-design-ref-phase-3-vision-codification-of-the-corpus-into-in/">#396</a>). The
  phase-1 pipeline (<a href="/backlog/382-design-reference-screenshot-corpus-collect-dedup-codify/">#382</a>)
  already ships, but its inclusion gate is a <strong>deterministic, hand-authored</strong>
  <code>readySelector</code> (<code>scripts/design-refs.mjs:145</code>): it only works when a human has
  written the right CSS selector for that one target, doesn't generalise, and can't distinguish a clean
  application surface from a marketing splash, a modal-obstructed view, or a stale error panel — the exact
  failures the corpus saw (Photopea's splash, Grafana's error page). Session report:
  <code>reports/2026-06-13-design-ref-vision-pipeline.md</code>.
</p>

<h2>The finding that decides the architecture</h2>
<p>
  Surveying UI-vision prior art surfaces an <strong>asymmetry</strong>: <em>coarse screen
  classification is mature and reliable, while full screenshot→structure recovery is still hard.</em>
  That asymmetry is the whole ruling — it says the cheap <em>gate</em> verdict can be automated with
  confidence, while the rich <em>codification</em> must stay human-in-the-loop.
</p>
