<h2>One swappable provider, two call shapes</h2>
<p>
  The two consumers differ in <em>cost and richness</em>, not in <em>kind</em> — both are “a vision model
  looks at a screenshot and returns structured judgement.” So they share <strong>one</strong>
  <code>customVisionProvider</code> registry (the
  <a href="/backlog/086-mockup-to-standard-code-tool/">#086</a> <code>customMockupAnalyzerRegistry</code>
  pattern — vision is infrastructure you plug in, not architecture you bake in, with no provider name in
  <code>scripts/design-refs.mjs</code> core), exposing two methods:
</p>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Consumer</th><th>Returns</th><th>Cost</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><code>classifyCandidate(frame, ctx)</code></td>
      <td>#475 capture-QC gate (collect time)</td>
      <td><code>{ verdict ∈ {app, obstructed, marketing, error, blank, non-app}, reasons[], remediation? }</code></td>
      <td>cheap, per candidate</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>analyzeForCodification(shot, ctx)</code></td>
      <td>#396 codification (post-admission)</td>
      <td>surface / register / layout tags + recurring-paradigm candidates</td>
      <td>rich, per corpus shot</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>
<p>
  This applies the #086 ruling correctly: #086 used <em>two</em> registries for analyzer-vs-generator
  because they move at different speeds — but here both calls are <em>analysis</em>, so they belong on the
  one analyzer-style seam. Splitting them would force two model integrations and two upgrade clocks for one
  swappable point. The separate-and-decouple bias is honoured where it pays (provider vs. core, input
  vs. output), while the provider stays singular.
</p>

<h2>Posture — internal tooling, zero lock-in</h2>
<p>
  This is dev/CI research-corpus tooling with <strong>no project-facing lock-in</strong> (the same posture
  as the <a href="/research/design-ref-taxonomy/">design-ref-taxonomy</a> topic): bring-your-own model key,
  and nothing about the corpus or its consumers depends on which model graded it. Deterministic
  <code>readySelector</code> short-circuits stay a free fast-path — vision is the <em>general</em> gate that
  generalises to any target, not the <em>only</em> gate.
</p>

